    en: "New York's implied consent law at NY Vehicle and Traffic Law § 1194 provides that any driver on a NY public highway has consented to a chemical test of breath, blood, urine, or saliva when arrested for DWI or other alcohol-related driving offenses. Refusing the test triggers a separate civil administrative case at the DMV — license revocation for at least 1 year (18 months for commercial drivers) plus a civil penalty of $500. Refusal is also admissible as evidence at the criminal DWI trial. The law distinguishes between roadside portable tests (which the driver may refuse without administrative penalty) and the post-arrest chemical test at a station (which triggers the implied consent consequences if refused)."
